    "recap_headline": "Fresno State Athletics",
    "recap_text": "FRESNO, Calif. \u2013\nDespite a strong offensive showing and an early six-run lead, Fresno State fell to Nevada, 15\u201312, on Saturday afternoon at Pete Beiden Field at Bob Bennett Stadium.\nThe Bulldogs totaled 17 hits and scored in six different innings, but Nevada used a nine-run seventh inning to erase Fresno State's advantage and take control of the Mountain West contest.\nWith the loss, Fresno State moved to 7-10 overall and 0-2 in Mountain West play, while Nevada improved to 10-6 and 2-0 in conference action.\nMIkey Boyd led the Bulldogs offensively with a 3-for-3 performance, driving in three runs and scoring three times.\nRyan De La Maza\nadded three RBIs with a pair of hits, while\nJett Ruby\nhomered and drove in two.\nAustin Young\nalso collected three hits and an RBI for Fresno State.\nHOW IT HAPPENED\nFresno State struck quickly in the first inning when\nOwen Faust\nled off with a ground-rule double before\nJett Ruby\nlaunched a two-run home run to right field to give the Bulldogs an early 2\u20130 lead.\nThe Bulldogs broke the game open in the third.\nMikey Boyd\ncrushed a two-run home run to right field,\nRyan De La Maza\nlater added an RBI single, and\nAustin Young\ndrove in another run with a double as Fresno State built a 6\u20130 advantage.\nNevada got on the board with a sacrifice fly in the fourth, but Fresno State responded immediately in the bottom half when Boyd delivered an RBI single to push the lead to 7\u20131.\nThe Wolf Pack began to chip away in the fifth with a pair of solo home runs and two additional runs to cut the Bulldogs' lead to 7\u20135. Fresno State answered again in the bottom of the inning when De La Maza blasted a solo home run to left field.\nThe Bulldogs extended the lead to 11\u20135 in the sixth inning.\nGriffen Sotomayor\ndoubled home a run, De La Maza added a sacrifice RBI, and\nBJ Rodriguez\nscored on a Nevada error during a steal attempt.\nNevada flipped the game in the seventh inning with a massive rally. The Wolf Pack collected eight hits in the frame, highlighted by a grand slam from Jacob Waller, as Nevada scored nine runs to take a 14\u201311 lead.\nNevada added another run in the eighth inning to make it 15\u201311. Fresno State threatened late, scoring once in the ninth on an RBI single by\nMarcus Nolen\n, but the rally fell short as Nevada secured the win.\nNOTES\nFresno State finished with 17 hits, matching Nevada's total.\nMikey Boyd\nwas 3-for-3 at the plate, collecting 3 runs, 3 RBIs and a home run.\nRyan De La Maza\nmade his first start as a Bulldog and totaled 3 RBIs and a home run\nFresno State scored 11 runs through six innings before Nevada's nine-run seventh inning.\nUP NEXT\nThe Bulldogs will close out the series on Sunday with first pitch slated for 1:05 p.m. PT."
